Ghana, the worldâ€™s second-biggest
cocoa producer, will increase by 33.3 percent the price farmers
are paid for beans during the 2010-11 harvest that will begin on
Oct. 1, Finance Minister Kwabena Duffuor said.  Cocoa beans will fetch a fixed rate of 3,200 cedis ($2,242)
per metric ton, from 2,400 cedis during the previous harvest,
Duffuor told reporters in the capital, Accra, today.  To contact the reporter on this story:
